def plot_yearly_average(ranges=[[0, 10], [10, 25]], x = 'PM-10', year_range=2000):
    traces = []
    for item in ranges:
        for index, gu in enumerate(gu_list_eng[item[0]:item[1]]):
            gu_data = yearly.loc[yearly['Place_Measured'] == gu]
            if year_range != 2000:
                gu_data = gu_data.loc[gu_data['Year'] >= year_range]
            traces.append(go.Scatter(
                x = gu_data['Year'],
                y = gu_data[x],
                mode = 'lines+markers',
                name = str(gu)))

        layout = dict(title = "Yearly average {} level of Seoul's Districts from {} to 2019 ({} Districts shown)".format(x, str(year_range), str(item[1] - item[0])),
                      xaxis= dict(title= 'Year',ticklen= 5,zeroline= False),
                      yaxis= dict(title= x, ticklen=5),
                      hovermode = 'closest'
                     )
        fig = dict(data = traces, layout = layout)
        iplot(fig)

# Seoul Air Quality Analysis
Using processed data from the previous kernel. 

Air pollution has solidified as a major societal issue in Seoul, a huge metropolitan city where I came from. It is widely accepted among the public that factories and energy use, as well as moving air currents from China, all affect the air in Seoul. While much of the public blames China for its polluted air moving across the Korean Peninsula, the Ministry of Environment of Korea determined that poluttion generated within Korea is a bigger factor. 

In this kernel, I will explore Air Quality data in more depth and try to find any interesting patterns. I collected data from all 25 districts in Seoul. 

Map of districts in Seoul:
![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Map_Seoul_districts_de.png/600px-Map_Seoul_districts_de.png)
